"Abstract The recent US. test cases involving peer_to_peer service providers such as Napster and Huckster have flushed into the open the debate over where to strike the balance between the rights of consumers and content producers. The fundamental issue is the same whether the content is film, music, or software. Should the freedom that consumers have traditionally enjoyed be curtailed in the interests of intellectual copyright protection? Related to this is the question of what technical measures are feasible to protect against both pirating and unauthorized use of or access to content."
